cmCourseInfo.description: Principles of neurophysiology, endocrinology and reproductive physiology for students enrolled in Life Science programs.
cmCourseInfo.title: Human Physiology I
cmCourseInfo.recommendedPreparation: BIO130H1; CHM136H1/ CHM151Y1; and 1.0 credit from any of the following: MAT135H1, MAT136H1, MAT137Y1, MAT157Y1, PHY131H1, PHY132H1, PHY151H1, PHY152H1

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

This is an online course. Lectures will be posted online (4-6 hours/week). Students will have the opportunity for a synchronous online help session 1-2 hrs/week to ask questions and clarifications about lecture content with the professor (the session will be recorded). There will also be in-person tutorials, please select a tutorial time during enrolment. Students need the ability to view PDF files and must have access to Quercus.  All  test will take place in person during scheduled class time. The final in-person exam will be announced by the Faculty of Arts and Science.

The lectures will be posted to watch asynchronously but help sessions & tests will run synchronously. This means students must be available Tuesdays and Thursdays 5-7 p.m (Toronto time).

Delivery Instructions

The lecture videos will be posted to watch asynchronously but help sessions, tutorials & tests will run synchronously. This means students have to ensure they are available Tuesdays and Thursdays 5-7 p.m. (Toronto time).

cmCourseInfo.description: An opportunity to go outside of the traditional university classroom and actively participate in a marine mammal autopsy. Learn the diversity and adaptive nature of marine mammalian physiology/anatomy as it compares to human. The course is 2 weeks (in May), one week of hands-on tissue dissection, and one week of group discussions of the findings and draft report preparation. Not eligible for CR/NCR option. An additional fee is required to help cover the cost of delivery for this course. Please see https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl378h1f for details.
cmCourseInfo.title: Field Physiology: Marine Mammal Autopsy
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BIO270H1, BIO271H1/PSL201Y1/PSL280H1/PSL300H1, PSL301H1 or permission of the course coordinator

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

This is a two weeks intensive summer field course from May 15-26, 2023. Week one will be in-person at the University of Toronto, week two will be done virtually.   
Additional information and application may be obtained at https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl378h1f 
Space is limited and requires course director approval no later than April 1, 2023 . Please note: an ancillary fee is required to help cover the cost of the delivery of this course addition to the university registration.  See http://www.physiology.utoronto.ca/psl378h1f for details.

 

Delivery Instructions

Week one will be in-person at the University of Toronto, week two will be delivered online synchronously.

courses.name: Comparative Marine Mammal Physiology in the Field

cmCourseInfo.description: Hands-on monitoring of physiological measures with live dolphins, manatee and sea lions; field observations and applied learning to a physiology project. Two-weeks at the end of April early May: 1st week is spent at the marine research center in Mexico, 2nd week of wrap-up discussion and integration of data at U of T. Not eligible for CR/NCR option. An additional fee is required to help cover the cost of delivery for the course. See https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl379h for details.
cmCourseInfo.title: Comparative Marine Mammal Physiology in the Field

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

This is a two weeks intensive virtual summer field course from May 1 - 12, 2023.   
Additional information and application may be obtained in https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl379h

Space is limited and requires course director approval no later than April 1, 2023 . Please note: an ancillary fee is required to help cover the cost of the delivery of this course in addition to the university course fees. Fees for PSL379H online virtual course covers the personnel and the marine mammal facilities (trainers, staff and to record the in-water sessions).  Please see https://physiology.utoronto.ca/psl379h for details.

 

Delivery Instructions

The Department of Physiology will be offering a two weeks ‘up close and personal virtual experience’ with various species of dolphins & seals.  The first week is spend on Zoom visiting our marine mammals and the second week will be daily Zoom class meetings to discuss individual projects, group discussion of the information learned and applied.
